description.plain:
All you need to know about The National is that they gave up good jobs for this. But perhaps you want more.

They are five friends from Cincinnati, Ohio, who started making music in 1999 when they found themselves living near one another again in Carroll Gardens, Brooklyn.

They weren’t looking to take over the world with a demo and matching outfits. Rather, music was their way of letting off steam from those good jobs. Records are what they talked about when they went out drinking together, when they ate together, when they played wiffle ball in the summertime.

songs.title: Abel

description.plain:
At SongMeanings.com a user named _yoda writes:

When I saw The National live at the City Recital Hall in Sydney (first show), Matt remarked wryly just before the song began: “This is a song about love… between two brothers”.

The title is a reference to the story in Genesis.  Cain is Abel’s older brother.  Because God likes Abel’s sacrifice more than Cain’s, Cain becomes jealous and kills his brother.  God asks Cain “Where is Abel?”, and Cain answers “I don’t know.  Am I by brother’s keeper?”.  God curses Cain.

The narrator of the song appears to be represented by Cain, who is out of control and asking his brother for help, sympathy, or something else.

description.plain:
“Ada” follows the singer as he converses with a female named Ada. She seems to be the singer’s love interest/close relative/good friend who suffers from social anxiety.

This can be assumed due to the rather soothing instrumentation and tone of voice used when singing as if gently and patiently giving advice to someone.

The song also features melodic, soothing, and delicate piano playing from Sufjan Stevens, which adds to the song’s atmosphere.

songs.title: Afraid of Everyone

description.plain:
The ghostly and brassy “Afraid of Everyone”  features Sufjan Stevens on background vocals, and builds patiently in typical National style. Its key refrain is evocative of the midlife issues Matt Berninger’s baritone chronicles so aptly.

In an interview, guitarist Aaron Dessner explained:

Sufjan came in one day when we were struggling with ‘Afraid Of Everyone’ – that song was very difficult to make happen – and he just started playing the harmonium and singing along with it. He made up this little melody and he layered it four times – that gave the song a whole different dimension. That was his contribution.

songs.title: Cardinal Song

description.plain:
This is the first track off of “Sad Songs for Dirty Lovers”, and also the first step that The National really took into becoming more than an alt-country band.
Some of the instrumentation and arrangement show their origins to be sure, but this song heralded their descent into a world where there is no break from shooting up the ladder.
Also, this song is key to understanding the relationship between men and women in early The National songs. It lays out the power struggles that Matt always seems to lose in the end.

description.plain:
The song’s title refers to the Empire Service, a higher-speed commuter train that provides daily service between New York City and Albany, NY. This 460 miles train line is known as the Empire Corridor and is a likely means of travel between the Brooklyn-based band’s members and Aaron Dessner’s Long Pond Studio in Upstate NY.

He uses the distance of the train line as a metaphor, as he so often does, for growing distance in a long-standing relationship.

The drum machine and synths turn a sweet melodic hook into a distancing mechanism, playing into the theme of the song.

songs.title: Exile Vilify

description.plain:
This song is an easter egg in the video game Portal 2. Originally, it was intended as a “fake ending,” where the player would find a hole in the roof of Aperture Science, and the moon would be visible. The player would shoot a portal at the moon and would be sucked in. Once the player dies, credits would roll, and “Exile Vilify” would play in the background. This easter egg, however, was removed, due to how playtesters easily overlooked it.

The whole song evokes the relationship between the main character, Chell, and the first game’s antagonist, GLaDOS, as the former navigates the deadly Aperture Science Computer-Aided Enrichment Center. Fragments of the lyrics appear on the walls of the facility in a hidden section, where the song is playing on a radio.



It is possible that the song is intended to be from the point of view of one of the background characters, Doug Rattman, who is ostensibly the one who scrawled the lyrics (among other graffiti) on the walls of the Enrichment Center.

songs.title: Fake Empire

description.plain:
The opening track of The National’s 2007 opus, “Fake Empire” describes the hedonism and escapism of a culture lost to excess in the wake of its diminishing status as a world superpower. Simply, the everyday demands of life are too difficult for us to really care about America’s sociopolitical climate, therefore we are “half-awake” to these concerns in our “fake empire.”

The song features a prominent piano riff (a C major progression) providing the melody and ends with a brass ensemble.

description.plain:
A poster on SongMeanings.com claims that he interviewed Matt Berninger, and Matt told him:


It was based on an actual event in his life between him and a friend. The song is about a friend who was in a tough situation and Matt, trying to be a good friend, gave him advice. However, this advice only lead his friend off in the opposite direction and ultimately brought even worse results. He said he felt terrible afterwards and just had this sinking guilt that was hanging over his head.

Matt never said exactly what the situation was or it’s results, nor did he say whether him and his friend ended up alright.

songs.title: Green Gloves

description.plain:
The title “Green Gloves” may be a metaphor for jealousy (which is sometimes called “the green monster” in literature).

However, the song is actually about remembering someone by trying to be like them.

Matt Berninger in an interview with Paste Magazine:

It’s more about trying to remember someone and sort of be them—someone that you’ve lost your connection with (maybe because of a death)—so you reconnect with them by getting inside their clothes, watching their videos, getting in their bed. You’re actually recreating them somehow in order to know them better. You miss them so much you have to become them.

description.plain:
I Am Easy to Find is a 2019 American short film directed by Mike Mills starring Alicia Vikander. The film was released on May 13, 2019 on the official The National YouTube page. The short is shot in black and white and features Vikander playing a woman from birth to death.

In a statement about I Am Easy to Find, Mills detailed his unusual collaborative process with the indie-rock act.
“The National gave me the stems for their songs, some were sketches some were finished and encouraged and allowed me to create my own versions of the songs to score the film,” he said. “The album then features different versions of these same seven songs — and nine new songs which sometimes refer to the themes, texts, ideas from the film but are their own work, their own piece of art.”

Tom and Matt are almost a decade apart in age and have separate personalities; Matt being the professional son who started enjoying success with The National in the past few years, and Tom struggling to make a career as a filmmaker.

After Matt hired Tom as a roadie for their 2010 High Violet tour with intents of keeping him employed and furthering their relationship as brothers, Tom behaved unprofessionally, too distracted filming what would become the documentary Mistaken For Strangers (watch the trailer here) and was eventually fired.

Still feeling guilty about Tom’s state of mind, Matt took him in to his apartment as Tom pieced together footage for the documentary, and wrote this song to admit his failings as an older brother and a testament to their brotherly love.

A song about the loneliness of living in a nowhere town where nothing ever seems to happen. As The National originates from Ohio, endearingly referred to as a flyover state, the band seems to draw from their own past life experiences for the themes of this song.

Anyone who has ever lived in exile in a small town can surely relate to this track which perfectly incapsulates the lonely emptiness of such places.

songs.title: Lemonworld

description.plain:
“Lemonworld” is the 7th track on High Violet. A “Lemonworld” is a heaven, an oasis to escape the city, especially New York :

“A Lemonworld is an invented, sexy, weird place where you can escape from New York.” – Matt Berninger

Still, the song is not about a Lemmonworld, but about the two sisters living there. They invite Matt out to come to their place out of the city and it gets late so he stays over and they enjoy the odd fun day that comes as a surprise. Matt suggests they put on their bathing suits while he tries to find some music on their cd collection that has no emotional meaning for him, like anything from the Smiths, which he has listened to so many times that it becomes painful to hear. Or maybe they have a karaoke and he sings a silly song until he looses his breath.
So they go on with their party and he consumes some expensive sustance that makes him dizzy and the sisters start asking him too many questions so he dismisses them and they have an unexpected Summer party where he, in his stupor, locates the sisters in this Lemmonworld that he’d like to die in.

songs.title: Light Years

description.plain:
“Light Years” is the closing track and second single from The National’s eighth album, I Am Easy To Find. It was premiered live before its release on April 29, 2018, during the second night at the band’s own Homecoming Festival, in Cincinnati.

In an interview with NME on April 27, 2018, Matt Berninger told that the band “have been recording wherever they went”:

We’ve been in the studio. We’ve been recording wherever we go. We had a bunch of stuff that we just recorded in Buenos Aires when we were in South America just because we had a day or so. We’ve been constantly just writing. Even before Sleep Well Beast was done, there was already a bunch of stuff cooking, but when Trump won it just didn’t feel right for whatever reason. I can’t even tell you why. Sleep Well Beast had the pivot when the world changed. We stayed in the kitchen. We don’t do that thing where we don’t talk to each other for months anymore. I don’t know what form or when this next album is going to come out, but we’ve been doing some other really interesting collaborations with people too. It’s all way more than halfway done.

songs.title: Mr. November

description.plain:
The song is about a wealthy, “blue blood”, white man feeling nervous and insecure.  The title references the United States' election day: the first Tuesday after the first Monday in November.

In this interview with Vice, Matt Berninger says

We don’t think of ourselves as a political band. If you read into the lyrics of any of our supposedly political songs, they aren’t partisan messages. They aren’t protests. We made t-shirts for Obama that said “Mr. November,” but that song was actually written about John Kerry and how uncomfortable it must be to run for president. It must be so stressful and annoying to constantly play that role.



Unfortunately, the link to actually purchase the t-shirts is dead.

description.plain: Used in the short film “I Am Easy To Find” multiple times, Oblivions is a ballad about how love eventually carries the other into a perpetual chasm of oblivion, and the singer (Tindle) is okay with it because she trusts him. description.plain:
On the Sound Exploder podcast, lead singer and co-writer Matt Berninger explains:

“[‘Sea of Love’ is] a romantic song about a man who’s bitten into the apple a little bit. It’s a big murky mess of all the feelings that happen between human beings when romance and hopes, and all those kinds of things, they run away with our hearts a little bit. […] And then the song just started to become this loose idea of how people often will fall in love and jump into a situation. The ‘Joe’ is definitely the one who is jumping in with both feet. There’s a room full of people who are all sliding into the sea of love.

The song’s music video, directed by Sophia Peer, is an homage to the video for “Grubiy Zakat” from Russian indie rock band Zvuki Mu.

Matt Beringer commented on this song in an interview at neumu.net


This song, [Beringer] explains, is set in the neighborhood of Brooklyn where he and Bryce Dessner lived during the recording of Alligator, a place called Ditmas Park.

“It’s a beautiful neighborhood that feels more like Savannah, Georgia than Brooklyn,” he said. “The houses are all free-standing with nice yards and wrap-around porches. I was sitting outside one night watching a bunch of kids running up and down Beverly setting off car alarms. The song is theirs. Recording out there was nice, very relaxed.”


The band performed this track at the wedding of producer Peter Katis. A photo of the band performing on stage, with couples dancing in the foreground, became the cover of the band’s next album, Boxer, released in 2007.
